AIR FORCE RESERVE OFFICER

DEPARTMENT OF THE AIR FORCE 
INSTRUCTION 36-2903

TRAINING CORPS 
Supplement 

18 NOVEMBER 2021 

Personnel 

DRESS AND PERSONAL APPEARANCE OF AIR FORCE PERSONNEL 

COMPLIANCE WITH THIS PUBLICATION IS MANDATORY 

ACCESSIBILITY:  Publications  and  forms  are  available  on  the  Maxwell  Pub

lications  and 

RELEASABILITY:  There are no releasability restrictions on this publication. 

Forms Management Office AF Portal Web page for downloading. 

OPR: HQ AFROTC/DOS 
Supersedes AFI36-2903_AETCSUP_AFROTCSUP, 24 August 2020 

Certified by: HQ AFROTC/DO (Col Michael Wyatt) 
Pages:  25 

This supplement  implements and extends the guidance  contained  in DAFI 36-2903, Dress and 
Personal

Appearance  of  Air  Force  Personnel.  Users  must  read  this  supplement  in  conjunction 
with implemented publications. It establishes Air Force ROTC (AFROTC) guidance regarding the 
wear of Air Force uniform items and personal appearance standards of cadets. Refer recommended 
changes and/or corrections to this publication to the Office of Primary Responsibility (OPR) using 
the AF Form 847,

Recommendation for Change of Publication, through your chain of command. 
Supplements to this publication are not allowed. Request for waivers must be processed through 
command channels to the publication OPR for consideration. Ensure that all records created as a 
result of processes prescribed in this publication are maintained in accordance with AFI 33-322, 
Records Management Information Gov

ernance Program, and disposed of in accordance with the 
Air  Force  Records  Information  Management  System  (AFRIMS)  Records  Disposition  Schedule 
(RDS).  The provisions of this supplement apply to all AFROTC senior units, to include cadets.  
The use of the name or mark of any specific manufacturer, commercial product, commodity, or 
service in this publication does not imply endorsement by

the Air Force. 

SUMMARY OF CHANGES 

This publication incorporates DAFI36-2903_AFGM2020-01 and provides guidance on OCP and 
United  States  Space  Force  (USSF)  uniform  wear  for  cadets  to  include  wear  of  the  USSF 
Distinguished Lapel Insignia for the Service and Mess Dress Coats. Additionally, all references to 
the Two-Piece Flight Duty Uniforms or 2PFDUs, and Airman Battle Uniforms

or ABUs have been 
deleted, along with uniform items POC cadets are authorized to wear. Aircrew Style Name Patch 
(ASNP) is now being referred to as “Flight Duty Uniform (FDU) Name Patch. This current version 
also  aligns  with  each  respective  section  and  the  overall  layout  of  DAFI  36-2903,  which  was 
updated on 15 March 2021. 

 2 

DAFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

1.2.5.

1. (Added) Alteration and Exchange. Cadets will not alter any uniform item without prior 
approval from the uniform custodian; if alterations are approved by the uniform custodian, cadets 
will not use personal funds. Custom tailoring (having uniforms custom-fitted for the wearer) of 
uniforms is not allowed. Basic hemming and normal  alterations  necessary  for regular  wear  are 
allowed.  EXCEP

TION:  Cadets  who  have  purchased  their  own  uniforms  are  authorized  to 
alter/tailor their uniforms  if approved by  the  detachment cadre  at their  own  expense.  Uniform 
items being altered will be IAW DAFI 36-2903.  

1.2.12. (Added) General Cadet Uniform Wear. Cadets will wear an authorized military uniform 
for a full day at least once per week at PMT events. Wear of the uniform for

AFROTC academic 
classes on school days other than LLAB is at the Det/CC’s discretion. 

1.2.12.1. (Added) Uniform Wear Off Campus. Uniform wear in off-campus facilities should be 
comparable to that of  clothing  worn  by civilians in the establishment. Operational  Camouflage 
Pattern  (OCP)  is  the  appropriate  uniform  if  civilians  are  dressed  in  casual  attire.  Blues  are 
appropriat

e if civilians will be in business casual attire. Service dress is appropriate if the event is 
coat and tie. Mess dress or equivalent is appropriate for black tie evening attire. 

1.2.12.1.1. (Added) OCP, and Flight Duty Uniform (FDU). Cadets may wear the OCP or FDU off-
campus  to  dine  in  local  establishments  frequented  by  civilian  workers  wearing  work  clothing 
comparable to the OCP

or FDU regardless of whether or not the establishment offers wait staff 
service. Cadets are cautioned to select a dining establishment that satisfies these criteria.  If the 
dress code of the establishment, whether written or unwritten, is of more formal dress, the OCP or 
FDU will not be worn in the establishment. Cadets will not wear these uniforms to off-campus 
establishments  to  do  exten

ded  shopping,  dining,  socializing  or  to  take  part  in  any  form  of 
entertainment. However, short convenience stops are authorized in the OCP or FDU. Det/CCs may 
set a more specific policy on specific local establishments acceptable for OCP, or FDU wear. 

1.2.12.2. (Added) Uniform of the Day and Leadership Lab (LLAB). Cadets will wear the uniform 
of the day for the full day of LLAB eve

nts. The Det/CC and/or OFC will decide which uniform 
combination will be worn depending on the LLAB activity of the day. The service dress uniform 
must be worn at LLAB at least once per term. 

1.2.12.3.  (Added)  Military  Institutions.  At  institutions  classified  as  Senior  Military  Colleges 
(SMC) where distinctive types of uniforms are required, AFROTC cadets will wear the uniform 
pres

cribed in institutional  directives. Special attention must  be paid to  ensuring  cadets at these 
institutions  are  trained  on  proper  wear  of  the  Air  Force  uniform  prior  to  participation  in  Field 
Training and commissioning. 

1.2.12.4.  (Added)  Field  Training  Uniforms.  FT  uniform  requirements  differ  slightly  from 
detachment requirements. FT uniform requirements checklist

can be found in the Field Training 
Manual. 

1.2.13. (Added) USSF-Select Cadets.  

1.2.13.1. (Added) Physical Training (PT) Gear. USSF-select cadets will wear U.S. Air Force PT 
Gear IAW DAFI 36-2903, until U.S. Space Force PT Gear is available. 

 DAFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

3 

1.2.13.2.  (Added)  Service  Dress  Uniform.  USSF-select  cadets  will  wear  the  United  States

Air 
Force (USAF) Service Dress as outlined in paragraphs 4.5.1.2–4.1.7.7.1.1. Additionally, USSF-
select cadets are authorized to wear the U.S. Space Force Distinguished Lapel Insignia on their 
Service Coats. The USSF Distinguished Lapel Insignia will be worn centered below the lapel notch 
on the widest portion of the Service Coat lapel. The insignia will be worn on both lapels similar to 
how

the US insignia is worn on both lapels. 

1.2.13.2.1. (Added) Only one of the USSF Distinguished Lapel Insignia will be worn on the men’s 
blue shirt and the women’s blue blouse.  Both men and women will wear one insignia centered ½ 
inch above the nametag. 

1.2.13.3. (Added) Mess Dress Uniform. USSF-select cadets will wear the USAF Mess Dress as 
outlined  in  paragraph  4.1.3.  Additionally,

USSF-select  cadets  are  authorized  to  wear  the  U.S. 
Space  Force  Distinguished  Lapel  Insignia  on  their  Mess  Dress  coat.  The  USSF  Distinguished 
Lapel Insignia will be worn on the wearer’s right and ½ inch above all other badges. 

1.2.14.  (Added)  Events  Authorized  for  Uniform  Wear.  Cadets  participating  in  detachment 
sanctioned Color Guards, Honor Guards, and Drill Team

s may wear their uniforms while preparing 
for, performing, or coming from performing Color/Honor Guard or Drill Team duties. Military 
institutions retain the same exception to uniform wear as in paragraph 1.2.12.3. 

1.2.14.1. (Added) Definitions. In order to ensure all detachments have the same understanding of 
what constitutes these organizations, the following definitions are provided. 

1.2

.14.1.1. (Added) Color Guard. Color Guards are small (typically 3-8 person) teams that form 
to carry the flags/colors and present them at such activities as sporting events, parades, and other 
formal  ceremonies,  such  as  military  balls.  These  teams  may  also  participate  in  Color  Guard 
competitions at drill meets. 

1.2.14.1.2. (Added) Honor Guard. Honor Guards are small (typically 3-

8 person) teams that are 
very similar to Color Guards, except they may or may not carry flags. They are formed to honor 
something  or  someone,  such  as  at  funerals,  veterans’  ceremonies,  etc.  This  may  include  flag 
raising/lowering details. 

1.2.14.1.3. (Added) Drill Team. Drill Teams are normally larger teams (though sometimes as small 
as a color/honor guard) that do not carry flag

s, except a flight guidon in some situations. They may 
drill  with  or  without  weapons.  They  are  formed  to  perform  for  events  such  as  parades  or 
exhibitions, or to compete in Drill Team competitions at drill meets. 

1.3.3.1. (Added) Military Aircraft. Cadets will wear OCP or FDU while traveling aboard military 
aircraft  between  military  installations.  Det/CC  may  authorize  we

ar  of  civilian  clothes  or 
detachment polos if uniforms have not been issued. 

1.3.4.1. (Added) Commercial Aircraft. Cadets will not wear any AFROTC uniform while traveling 
aboard commercial aircraft unless specifically directed to do so. 

 4 

DAFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

1.3.7. (Added) Exceptions. General Military Course (GMC) cadets may not wear the items listed 
below. O

nly Professional Officer Course (POC) cadets may wear the following items which are 
purchased at their own expense with Det/CC approval: 

1.3.7.1. (Added) Corfam shoes/Corfam pumps. 

1.3.7.2. (Added) Service caps. If worn for other than Color/Honor Guard or Drill Team purposes, 
wear the same insignia as active duty officers. Insignia must be purchased at the expense of the 
cadet. 

1.3.7.3. (

Added) Semi-Form Fitting Blouse (Long or Short-Sleeved).  

1.3.7.4. (Added) Tactical (baseball) OCP style caps. 

1.4.14. (Added) When NOT to wear the AFROTC Uniform. Det/CCs have discretion to enforce a 
professional military image and may restrict uniform wear  as necessary. A cadet with a failing 
BMI or body fact check is permitted to wear the uniform if a current passing PFA is on file. 

1.

5.4.1.  (Added)  Authorized  Uniform  Items.  Uniform  items  not  listed  in  this  instruction  but 
authorized for wear per  DAFI  36-2903 may be authorized  for  cadets  if purchased  at their own 
expense. However, detachment cadre should not encourage or discourage cadets to use personal 
funds to purchase items not covered in this instruction. Cadets must ensure they are wearing the 
unifor

m item properly, including the wear of cadet rank insignia.  

1.5.4.2.  (Added)  Procurement  of  Maternity  Uniform.  AFROTC/DOS  will  purchase  maternity 
uniforms for wear by cadets with approval from the Det/CC. Det/CCs may waive uniform wear 
for pregnant cadets during the timeframe they are unable to wear the regular uniform. 

1.5.4.3. (Added) Mess Dress Wear. Costs associated with wear o

f the mess dress uniform are paid 
by the cadet. 

1.5.5. (Added) Detachment Responsibilities. 

1.5.5.1.  (Added)  Detachments  will  not  issue  a  uniform  to  a  student  until  all  application 
requirements  are  complete  and  the  student  is  currently  eligible  or  will  be  eligible  (as  can  be 
reasonably ascertained) for the planned semester of membership. 

3.4. Tattoos/Brands/Bod

y Markings. Det/CCs have the responsibility to approve or disapprove 
tattoos for applicants and cadets IAW DAFI 36-2903 and any subsequent guidance in DAFI 36-
2903. Det/CCs will provide documentation via AF Form 4428 for any cadet with unauthorized or 
inappropriate  tattoos  stating  that  the  cadet  has  been  counseled  on  AFROTC  and  Air  Force 
requirements and has begun removal of the u

napproved tattoos. 

3.4.1.1. Cadets with inappropriate tattoos anywhere on the body (to include those that are obscene 
or advocate sexual, racial, ethnic or religious discrimination, or that are prejudicial to good order 
and discipline and bring discredit upon the Air Force) must be in the process of removing these 
tattoos at their own expense before attending Field Training. 

 DAFI36-2903_AF

ROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

5 

4.1.3.  (Added)  Semi-Formal  or  Mess  Dress  Uniform.  Cadets  will  wear  the  semi-  formal  dress 
uniform or mess dress uniform when participating in AFROTC-related military ball/dining out. 
Headgear  will  not  be  worn  with  the  semi-formal  or  mess  dress  uniform.  Cadets  will  not  wear 
civilian clothing—evening gowns, dresses, suits—to their own

military ball/dining out. When the 
costs associated with wear of the semi-formal dress uniform are prohibitive, the Det/CC may give 
authorization for local wear of the service dress uniform at formal social functions. Wear of the 
mess dress uniform will be IAW DAFI 36-2903. POC cadets will wear silver sleeve braid. GMC 
cadets will not wear silver sleeve braid. Braid received with purchase of

the mess dress should be 
retained by the cadet for wear as POC cadet and upon commissioning. Hard Shoulder Boards with 
appropriate silver stripes will be worn on the Mess Dress. Hard shoulder boards will be purchased 
at the expense of the cadet. If detachments have hard shoulder boards available, they can be issued 
to cadets for wear with the mess dress uniform. Cadets should contact the unifo

rm custodian for 
commercial sourcing. 

4.1.3.1. (Added) Civilian clothing is only authorized for wear if the cadet is participating as a guest 
at another service’s military ball/dining out, or if the cadet falls into a category which does not 
authorize them to wear the uniform (see DAFI 36-2903 paragraph 1.4). 

4.5.1.2.  (Added)  Service  Dress  Uniform.  The  service  dress  uniform  is  the

official  uniform  for 
AFROTC training. The service dress uniform  consists of the service dress coat, trousers, long-
sleeved or short-sleeved shirts/blouses, tie/tie tab, as well as other required accoutrements (name 
tag, rank insignia, ribbons, badges, etc.). 

4.5.1.2.1. (Added) Cloth shoulder marks will be used on the epaulets of the service dress jacket, 
long-sleeved and short-sleeved s

hirts/blouses, and the sweater. The epaulets are inserted into the 
cloth shoulder marks and buttoned. The bottom edge of the cloth shoulder mark must be as close 
as possible to the upper seam of the sleeve. See attachment 2 Figure A2.4 for cadet rank insignia. 

4.5.2.2.1. (Added) Silver Name Tags. Only POC cadets wear the silver service dress name tag on 
the service dress jacket.  

4.5.2.2.2.

(Added) Shoulder Cords. In the short-sleeve Blues or long-sleeve Blues combination, 
authorized  shoulder  cords  are  optional.  In  the  service  dress  uniform,  authorized  cords  are 
mandatory. 

4.5.2.2.3.  (Added)  Braids.  Braids  will  not  be  worn  on  the  service  dress  coat.  If  a  braid  was 
previously  sewn  on,  it  does  not  need  to  be  removed,  but  ensure  the  jacket

is  only  issued  to 
contracted  cadets  if  at  all  possible.  Remove  from  inventory  through  sale  or  rotation.  Braids 
received with purchase of the service jacket will be retained and will be issued to commissioning 
cadets  if  the  uniform  is  purchased.  It  may  then  be  sewn  on  prior  to  commissioning  at  the 
commissioning cadet’s expense. 

4.7.7.1. (Added) Headgear. Cadet

s will wear the officer flight cap with diamond braid (male or 
female) with the service dress uniform. Cadets will be issued “Prop & Wings” flight cap insignia 
(Figure 4.10) upon satisfactory completion of FT. 

4.7.7.1.1. (Added) POC cadets are authorized to wear gold/silver combination “Prop & Wings” 
(gold wings and silver propeller) if a relative was a member of the Army Air Corps, if a pare

nt has 

 6 

DAFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

at least 20 years of military service, if a parent died in the line of duty, or if a parent participated 
in active combat as a member of any U.S. military service. The gold/silver “Prop and Wings” is 
Vanguard Part # 3680101. Insignia must be purchased at the expense of the cadet. 

Figure 4.10. (Added) Prop & Wings. 

5.1.2.4.4. (Added)

Cadet Rank at Field Training (FT). Cadets will wear the rank of Cadet Third 
Class (C/3C) while participating in FT. 

5.1.2.4.5. (Added) Cadet Rank at Special Programs or Practical Military Training (PMT). GMC 
cadets will wear the rank of Cadet Third Class (C/3C) while participating in any Special Program 
or PMT between the AS 100 – AS 200 years and between the AS 200 – AS 300 years. POC cadets

will wear the last rank held at the detachment when participating in Special Programs or PMT. 

5.1.2.4.6. (Added) Cadet Training Assistants (CTA) will wear Cadet Colonel (C/Col) rank insignia 
while at FT. 

5.1.3.1. (Added) Detachment Morale T-shirts. Det/CCs may design and authorize cadets to wear 
a standardized color T-shirt for local wear at the detachment to be worn with the OCP and FDU.

T-shirts with the OCP and FDU will be Coyote Brown (Tan 499) in color. Det/CCs may prescribe 
unit designation emblems to be worn on the upper left side of chest, not  to exceed 5 inches in 
diameter.  

5.2.6.1.3.  (Added)  OCP  Detachment  Patches.  Cadets  are  authorized  to  wear  detachment  (unit) 
patches. Detachments are responsible for converting their approved color configured patch to

the 
approved Spice Brown color IAW CMAL No. 20-01. 

5.2.6.1.3.1. (Added) Right Sleeve. USAF cadets will wear subdued US flag patch. Detachment 
patches  will  be  worn  centered,  below  the  U.S.  flag  patch;  USSF-select  cadets  will  wear  the 
detachment patch centered horizontally and vertically. 

5.2.6.1.3.2.  (Added)  Left  Sleeve.  USSF-select  cadets  will  wear  the  full  color  U

S  flag  patch. 
AFROTC  patch  will  be  worn  centered  below  the  US  flag  patch;  USAF  cadets  will  wear  the 
AFROTC patch centered vertically and horizontally.  

 
 
 DAFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

7 

5.2.6.1.3.3. (Added) Funding and Manufacturing. MILPERS GPC (Fund Code 32) is authorized 
for use when procuring detachment and AFROTC patches from authorized commercial ven

dors. 
View CMAL No. 20-01 for a list of authorized vendors. 

5.2.6.1.3.4. (Added) OCP Nametapes. Nametapes, U.S. Air Force and U.S. Space Force tapes will 
be Velcro. USAF cadets will wear Spice Brown nametapes, USSF-select cadets will wear Space 
Blue nametapes. Cadets will not sew on any tapes on the OCP utility uniform. [EXCEPTION: 
see paragraph 1.2.5.1.] 

5.2.6.1.3.5. (Added) Cadet Rank In

signia. OCP Velcro ranks will be utilized on the OCP utility 
uniform. POC Cadets will secure the rank in the middle of the chest Velcro rank area, centered, 
with the silver stripes(s) oriented horizontally. GMC Cadets will secure the rank in the middle of 
the chest Velcro rank area, centered, with the short edge of the insignia parallel to the bottom of 
the Velcro squadron and the chevrons poi

nting upwards. Velcro ranks will be worn as pictured in 
the diagram below.  See Figure 5.3. 

Figure 5.3. (Added) OCP GMC and POC Velcro Rank. 

Figure 5.4. (Added) USSF-Select OCP Nametapes and Flag.  

7.1.3.3. (Added) Metallic rank is worn on the lightweight blue jacket and all-weather coat. Rank 
will  be  centered  on  both  epaulets  5/8ths-inch  from  the  shoulder  seam.  POC  cadets  wil

l  wear 
metallic black and silver cadet officer rank insignia with the silver stripe(s) parallel to the shoulder 
seam. GMC cadets will wear metallic blue and silver rank insignia with the point toward the neck. 

7.1.3.3.1. (Added) Lightweight Blue Jacket. AS 400 cadets and extended cadets are authorized to 
wear the embroidered USAF or USSF logo on the lightweight blue jacket. 

7.1.11. (Added)

Cold-Weather Parka and Coyote Brown Fleece. The OCP name tape and U.S. Air 
Force tape will not be worn on the parka. The OCP name tape and U.S. Air Force name will be 
worn on the fleece. 

7.1.11.1. (Added) Rank is not worn on the cold-weather parka, FDU, or flight jacket. Cadets will 
wear rank on the coyote brown fleece, Level 6 OCP jacket. Cadets will wear the Velcro rank on 

   
 
 
 8

AFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

the Velcro patch above the name-tape on the coyote brown fleece jacket. Metal rank will be worn 
on the Level 6 jacket; the rank pin will be centered on the jacket rank tab. GMC rank will have the 
chevrons pointing upwards. POC rank pins will have the bars oriented horizontally. 

7.2.5.1. (Added) Cadet Wear of Beret. Only cadets categorized as Special

Warfare (19Z) may wear 
the navy blue beret with the service dress, Blues, and OCP. The “Prop and Wings” insignia will 
be  worn  in  the  center  of  the  stiffener,  ¼  inch  above  and  parallel  to  the  headband.  Cadets  may 
purchase  the  navy  blue  beret  at  their  own  expense.  The  navy  blue  beret  is  Vanguard  Part  # 
CAP96029. 

Figure 7.11. (Added) Cadet Beret. 

7.2.10.4. (Ad

ded) Distinctive Headgear. Cadre and Cadet Training Assistants (CTA) members are 
authorized  distinctive  headgear  when  assigned  to  the  AFROTC  Field  Training  Staff  and  while 
performing Field Training events. The headgear will aid in rapid identification of cadre and CTA 
members  in  the  event  of  an  emergency.  The  headgear  will  be  standardized  by  the  AFROTC 
commander. 

7.

2.11. (Added) OCP Headgear. Cadets will wear the OCP patrol cap with the OCP uniform. After 
successful completion of FT, cadets are authorized to wear the Prop and Wings insignia on the 
OCP cap. The Prop and Wings will be centered on the front of the cap. Blocking of the cap is 
authorized. Name tape will be worn on the back of the OCP patrol cap.  

9.1.2.1. (Added) Cadet Aeronautical, Space, C

yberspace and Parachutist Badges. 

9.1.2.1.1. (Added) Cadet Pilot Badge. Cadets who meet one of the following criteria are authorized 
to  wear  the  Cadet  Pilot  Badge.  Cadets  who  meet  two  or  more  of  the  criteria  listed  below  are 
authorized to wear the Cadet Senior Pilot Badge (pilot wings with a star). 

9.1.2.1.1.1.  (Added)  Flown  solo  through  private  means,  CAP,  or  anoth

er  solo  flight  program. 
Documentation must be provided to detachment cadre to prove solo qualification. 

9.1.2.1.1.2. (Added) Successfully completed the USAFA Soaring program. 

9.1.2.1.1.3. (Added) Categorized as pilot. 

9.1.2.1.1.4. (Added) Cadets will not wear cadet pilot wings with a star and wreath. 

9.1.2.1.2. (Added) Cadet Combat Systems Officer (CSO) Badge. Cadets who are categorize

d as 
CSO will wear the Cadet CSO Badge or Cadet Senior CSO Badge as appropriate. 

 
 DAFI36-2903_AFROTCSUP     18 NOVEMBER 2021 

9 

9.1.2.1.2.1.  (Added)  Cadets  who  have  previously  earned  the  Cadet  Pilot  Badge  (solo  flight  or 
USAFA Soaring program) and are categorized as CSO, wear the Cadet Senior CSO Badge in lieu 
of the Cadet Senior Pilot Badge. 

9.1.2.1.2.2. (Added) Cadets wi

ll not wear cadet CSO wings with a star and wreath. 

9.1.2.1.3. (Added) Cadet Remotely Piloted Aircraft (RPA) Badge. Cadets who are categorized as 
RPA officers will wear the RPA badge. 

9.1.2.1.4. (Added) Cadet Air Battle Manager (ABM) Badge. Cadets who are categorized as ABM 
will wear the Cadet ABM Badge. 

9.1.2.1.5.  (Added)  Cadet  Missile  Badge.  Cadets  who  are  categorized  as  Missil

e  Operations 
Officers will wear the Cadet Missile Badge. Cadets will not wear Cadet Missile Badge with a star 
and wreath. 

9.1.2.1.6.  (Added)  Cadet  Space  Operations  Badge.  USSF-select  cadets  who  are  categorized  as 
Space Operations Officers will wear the Cadet Space Badge. Cadets will not wear the Cadet Space 
Badge with a star and wreath.  

9.1.2.1.7. (Added) Cadets who are catego

rized as Cyber officers will wear the Cadet Basic Cyber 
Badge. 

9.1.2.1.7.1. (Added) Cadets who also completed a summer program at the Air Force Institute of 
Technology (AFIT), the Advanced Course in Engineering (ACE)-Cyber Security Boot Camp or 
the Information Assurance Internship Program may wear the Cadet Senior Cyber Badge. 

9.1.2.1.7.2. (Added) Cadets will not wear cadet Cyber Badge wing

s with a star and wreath. 

9.1.2.1.8. (Added) Parachutist Badge. Cadets who have earned the parachutist badge through the 
USAFA Freefall program, Army Airborne Training, or other prior service qualifications may wear 
parachutist badge. 

9.3.26. (Added) Cadet Occupational Badges. 

9.3.26.1.  (Added)  Medical  Insignia.  Cadets  wear  the  appropriate  badge  upon  receiving  an 
allocation in

the Nurse or Pre-Health category. 

9.3.27. (Added) 

9.3.27.1. (Added)  CTA  Badge. The CTA badge  (see  Figure  9.1) will be  worn  upon successful 
completion of CTA duties. On the service dress jacket, the CTA badge will be worn on the right 
breast, centered ½ inch above the service dress name tag.  If worn with the Arnold Air Society 
(AAS)  Pin,  place  the  AAS  pin  ½  inch  above  the  C

TA  badge.  On  the  long-  or  short-sleeved 
shirt/blouse, wear the CTA badge centered and ½ inch above the blue name tag. 

9.3.27.2.  (Added)  Shoulder  Cords.  Cadets  will  wear  shoulder  cords  on  the  left  shoulder  of  the 
service uniform. Only one shoulder cord may be worn at a time. Shoulder cords should be worn 

 10

grounded to the up

per seam of the sleeve. When this is not practical, they may be worn attached
